All the new hair feels. 🥰 @hannah__atkins you are literally the best. I get asked all the time how I keep my hair so blonde and what I use on it. There is no magic trick. I get it done every 4 weeks. I know. A lot of maintenance. And money. Perks of being an ex hair stylist for me. Here is a trick though. We use @alteregoitalynorthamerica Bleach with 30 vol. and bump my roots with @davinesofficial 10.1.2 with 20. If you want the blonde but not the up keep, go in 4 weeks after your highlight and just get a root bump. That will get you by and extra 2 or 3 weeks. And (depending on your stylist😬) shouldn’t be to expensive. Usually skipping the blow dry will save you a buck as well. Tricks of the trade. 💁🏼‍♀️ Let me know your blonde problems to know and I’m happy to help!

Obsessed is an understatement. You all know I have had a hard time getting on board with this whole hand tied, weft extension era. Mostly because I always felt like they were too bulky, too itchy, and worried I was going to have a string come loose and look like I was 15 again with bad clip ins. Although they have gotten much better lately, I am blown away by the @lushlocks_bylatitude Genius Wefts. The hair is silky smooth from the roots to ends. No top lining of stubble that causes itchiness. Plus you can mix and match colors to create your own highlights so the color always blends perfectly. They lay so flat to my head I don’t even know they’re there, and I finally did not wake up with an itchy scalp or headache. I am so proud of @elmoussa_angel @jolene_latitude33hair for their creation. They both are the best in the biz, and have been doing every kind of extensions out there since Paris Hilton put in her first set of clip ins. No wonder they created the best hair yet. Ask your stylist to order you @lushlocks_bylatitude for your next new set of extensions and you’ll see what I mean. 💁🏼‍♀️💖💃🏼

I know I don’t talk about business too much but all this BTS footage is making me inspired. I was not a good student. I don’t have a college degree. I just followed what I loved and was good at. When @elmoussa_angel said to find a makeup line that we should sell at her new salon, I decided to take it as a sign and go all in. I had a handful of the right people in my corner that I knew would help and support me and that was enough. It took 2 years and big fat loan, from the day I decided to do it, to the day we launched. I was terrified every step along the way. The first year, Scott and I literally shipped out over $500k worth of makeup out of our 1 bedroom apartment. It was not glamorous. Owning a business is not glamorous. It’s hard. It’s emotional. You have to be able to take big risks, not look back, and not care what people think. But I wouldn’t change it for the world and I am deeply, deeply grateful for every single person that has placed an order with us and supported me along the way. This is just the beginning. @pinkdustcosmetics ✨💕💋

First of all how adorable is that?🥰🥰🥰 Cam pulled the barstool over, sat Scott down, and read him Brown Bear like a teacher. ❤️❤️❤️

Cameron turned 4 in May. He is perfect. Smart, handsome, sweet, loving, but the damn kid won’t talk! What I have learned so far as a parent… get your kid all the help you possibly can. Get all the opinions, evaluations, bla bla bla. BUT, at the end of the day, you have to trust your parental gut. We have had Cam in Speech since he turned 2. I have heard all of the diagnoses, recommendations, and opinions under the sun. Some good and helpful. Some insulting and couldn’t care less. This topic has worried me to no end. In my heart I knew…Cam is stubborn. (He IS my son). He doesn’t have a hearing problem, nothing is wrong with his brain, he doesn’t have a learning disability. He just doesn’t try to be like the other kids, and won’t participate with people he doesn’t feel comfortable with. Some people understood and agreed, some mom shamed and tried to make me feel like I was in denial 🙄. Same with potty training. He took a little longer to come around. Once he was ready, he has literally not had 1 accident. Seriously. My point to this whole story is trust your gut. You know your child better than anyone and don’t ever let anyone tell you different. ❤️❤️❤️

Here’s a fun fact you might not know about me… I used to be THE wedding, hair and makeup girl. Back in my youth. 😂 I would sometimes do 2 weddings a day on the weekends. That was A LOT of curling. All I ever heard was “my hair doesn’t hold curl.” Sometimes that was true but most of the time it’s not the hair. Here are some of the main reasons your curls won’t stay. 

✨ You are using the wrong curling iron. The @bioionic Extra Long Curling is a GAME CHANGER! All my girls who I’ve made buy this back me up in the comments. 

✨You don’t have the heat up high enough. As long as your hair is clean. You can hold that sucker at the highest heat next to your scalp for like 3-5 seconds and your hair will be fine. (That’s why you don’t spray before.) 

✨ Use smaller sections. The smaller the section, the tighter the curl, the longer it will last. 

✨ Flexible hold hair spray. No help. A good super hold hair spray with lock in those curls, without leaving you without leaving you like a sticky helmet head. I love @enjoyhaircare Super hold, or @oribe medium hold is great too! 

Let me know any questions and what hair tutorial you want next! 💖💖💖 

#curlingtutorial #hairtips #curlingtips #hairreel #hairhacks

He’s 4 years old, has to fall asleep every night playing with my hair, and I can’t get the damn kid out of my bed to save my life. I’d say we’re pretty bonded. I think breast feeding is beautiful, and bonding, and healthy, for SOME women. For me, not so much. It was painful, exhausting, and way too much work for not enough milk. I remember feeling such guilt that it was so hard me. and I dreaded every minute of it. My point is. If it works for you, and you love it, that’s amazing. If not, I am living proof. The bond is not to the boob. It’s to the mom. Happy mom=happy baby. Stay in your own lane and do what is best for you. ❤️❤️❤️

I don’t usually get too personal on our Pink Dust page, but going into the holidays it seems like a good time to get vulnerable. We are going on our 8th year in business and I can not express the gratitude I have for every single one of our customers. 

To any new or aspiring business owners out there, I want to remind you… 

-It doesn’t happen over night. It takes time. You not only have to build a customer base, but customer loyalty. 
- You have to put your business before everything else. Period.
- It is no one else’s business until your business is thriving. 
- Listen to your gut before you listen to advice. 
- Be grateful for every customer and every sale. Even if they’re a pain in the ass. 😂 
- If your terrified, your on the right path. 
- KEEP. GOING. 

If you are doing what you love, and it is for the right reasons you can not NOT be successful. ♥️♥️♥️
